article.headline: Oregon State 75, Nebraska 67
article.story:
LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- When Nebraska made a run, Oregon State
responded.

That's what Coach Judy Spoelstra expected the Beavers to do.

Even though Oregon State led by 10 points at halftime, "we were
still going to be aggressive offensively," Spoelstra said
Wednesday following the Beavers' 75-67 victory over Nebraska in the
second round of the Women's National Invitation Tournament.

"We were not about to be tentative and eat up the clock," she
said.

For a brief time, it appeared that strategy might have been
flawed for Oregon State (17-14), which is playing in its fourth
consecutive WNIT. Freshman Kiera Hardy ignited a rally that gave
the Cornhuskers a 55-52 lead with 6:56 remaining.

But the lead was short-lived.

"We just stayed aggressive," said Mandy Close, one of two
Oregon State players to score 17 points. "We pride ourselves on
not letting down."

After Nebraska cut the lead to 58-57, Close scored six
unanswered points.

Shannon Howell, a transfer from Nebraska, also scored 17 points
in her return to Lincoln. Oregon State's other starters finished
with double-figure points as well.

Hollye Chapman scored 14 points and grabbed a game-high 10
rebounds. Brina Chaney contributed 13 points, and Leilani Estavan
added 10 points for the Beavers.

Hardy, who finished with a game-high 20 points, was the only
Husker to score a field goal for nearly 10 minutes of play before
the 1:54 mark in the second half.

"I think we just tried so hard to fight back, we ran out of
gas," she said.

Nebraska fell behind by as many as 11 points in the first half.

"I think our defensive transition left something to be desired.
That was basically the difference," said Alexa Johnson.

Nebraska finishes the season 18-12, after going 8-20 last
season.

Oregon State advances to a third-round game against Creighton on
Wednesday.
